Updating Q1 estimates. Chinese manufacturing PMI fell to a record low 35.7 in February, even lower than the figure seen during the depths of the financial crisis. Non-manufacturing PMI plummeted to an all time low of 29.6 from 54.1. There is the potential for political smoothing of China’s economic data, but the fact that the National Bureau of Statistics published record low PMI figures suggest it is not trying to gloss over the figures. Therefore I am substantially increasing the probability of a below 4% GDP rate of growth.

Given the decrease in China's GDP growth rate from 14.2% in 2007 to 6.5% in 2018 (World Bank), I predict that this trend will continue, with a more drastic decrease expected due to the corona virus. I forecast, with 50% probability that the GDP growth rate will fall to between 5 and 5.5% for the first quarter of 2020, as the corona virus will likely be rising. Due to coronavirus' impact on the economy (consumer purchases, transportation, manufacturing, shipping) the GDP will likely feel the brunt of this troubling time for China.

China wants to maintain the appearance that they have this outbreak under control (regardless of reality) for domestic and international reasons. They need to maintain the mandate of heaven and prevent panic from spreading, as well as quell investor and industry fears, despite having closed down areas that accounted for 80% of their GDP and 90% of their exports last year [1]. Given China's history of manipulating its numbers (the CCP is most likely manipulating the reported numbers of infected and dead as well) and their strong interest and culture of saving face, they will give the appearance that their GDP has only somewhat slowed down in Q1 [2]. Q2 and Q3 reports will most likely be closer in line with the actual GDP growth, but will still be exaggerated. Furthermore, the 2019-nCov affects their standing geopolitically, giving them less leverage in their trade war with the United States, emboldening Hong Kong protests, harming the Silk Road, hindering investment in Africa, and providing ample opportunities for intelligence agencies to foster dissent among the population. Manufacturers will be spooked into diversifying their supply chain to prevent future delays in case of another event like this and China will want to quell their fears through putting up a strong front. China will report a dip, but nothing dramatic that cannot be quickly overcome. Overall, China has little reason to report the actual numbers and every reason to inflate their numbers in hopes of maintaining their economic and geopolitical momentum. To not do so would be political and economic suicide.

For the past eight quarter’s, China GDP growth rate has averaged between 6% and 7%, flattening out at 6% in Q3 and Q4 of 2019. However, with the outbreak of the coronavirus, China’s GDP growth will most likely slow as many workers are facing quarantine and several supply chains have halter. In 2014 with the outbreak of Ebola Africa, Guinea saw a sharp drop in GDP growth from 1.1% at the start of the year to 0.1% by the start of 2015. Similarly, Libera saw a drop in GDP growth from 7.1% at the end of 2013 to 0.7% in 2014 to -1.6% in 2016. (All statistics from tradingeconomics.com)

I've had a close look at the data for the last 18 quarters. The annual change has been dropping steadily since Q2 in 2018 (after having fluctuated between 106.8 and 107.0 for about 3 years) at an average rate of 0.18 per quarter until it stalled at 106.0 in Q3 and Q4 2019. If the previous trend picks up, it drops to about 105.8, or possibly skips to 105.6. I don't see any realistic scenario where it jumps well below 105.5. I don't really believe the Chinese will report a blip associated with the coronavirus, at least not in Q1.

SARS decreased China's 2003 GDP by 0.5-1%. nCoV is more contagious and disruptive. The Chinese economy is now much more service-oriented and reliant on supply chains for both domestic & foreign trade. Many nations have imposed travel bans to/from China. Chinese citizens are voluntarily reducing domestic consumption due to voluntary isolation. More importantly, there is growing fear and distrust of the government among the Chinese public. Based on the long incubation time and difficulty in controlling spread, I do not think nCoV will be controlled anytime soon. Thus, the contagion of fear negatively impact the Chinese economy (and worldwide). I believe nCoV will result in an drop by >3% this year, but Q1 2020 may be too soon to feel the full impact. Therefore, I think it will most likely result in a index of around 5% growth, with a significant possibility that this may turn into a full-blown national panic. https://foreignpolicy.com/2020/02/03/knock-on-effects-china-coronavirus-weak-economy-markets/ https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-01-31/the-coronavirus-is-more-dangerous-for-the-economy-than-sars
